The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt at the latest G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of world's leading developed economies' leaders, no one can say which of them will join the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could champion nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has lasted for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be towards convergence, and people appeared to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But lately, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world remains increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolving preferences of consumers (who are increasingly sophisticated), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such on-shoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars at home.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of merchandise globalization is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, the current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution reflects not just the slowdown in international trade growth.
Rich countries' consumers are much more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics and inexpensive "fast fashion," which has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements like the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on issues of obscure tribunals protecting foreign corporations' interests and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
The next crisis is that of refugees worldwide: particularly in Europe, the anxiety about this influx may be a precursor to a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are populations in advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It is not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head to advanced countries each year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend to experience things quickly and superficially rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory shows, a one-time interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper understanding or cooperation foundation.
Continuous interaction is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are reluctant to provide good or simply honest service to people who are unlikely to return.
Restaurants serve food that is mediocre (or worse) without a smile, taxi drivers scam you, and hoteliers lie about their amenities.
Moreover, this little game can suffer interruptions.
In places where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to trigger a profound economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a giant cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a magnificent Caribbean island or an ancient port of the Mediterranean), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Harmony of the Seas cruise ship aims to replicate all the world's climates.
In fact, this ship, longer than 30 meters and containing the Eiffel Tower, includes a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus and train companies do the same to ensure their clients' safety by letting them off at a famous site for a limited time, actually just long enough to take some photos.
This style of travel imposes constraints on local infrastructure capacity.
There is often not enough space to walk along Venice's canals or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual miscomprehension.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer trinkets or extremely expensive taxi rides.
The locals do not appreciate the groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain any sense of trust.
One easily feels a nostalgia for a time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and prolonged encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, for the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months in ancient monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse still, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Shortly after the entry of the United States into World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of packing up to move into the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance with Britain by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's anti-globalization populists.
